Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, Silicon Valley, West Coast
Full Description: Though VKLiQ started as a simple idea, they reached out to their audience of college students from multiple universities. They wanted their users to be connected to those that share similar interests. They wanted to consider the value of their time and location. Whether it was for a study group, campus related activities, private parties or events or a simple book club. Through these focus groups, they cultivated and refined the general need for their mobile app. Once the idea was refined, they returned to the students and presented the final plan. This proved successful. They were to deliver what they had asked for and what excited them about this application. Each group had expressed a large value and need for their product.     VKLiQ is a mobile platform that will deliver smart networking solutions and eCommerce to university campuses. VKLiQ is working with a vetted software development company to ensure a quality product by a qualified and invested group. Launching the product in a unique way will be their first step to capturing the audience. Again, this was identified in their focus groups of college students. Their goal is to visit multiple universities and create unique events that fit individuals and their interests. Events will be free to the user, requiring only that they have the app downloaded and user profile set on their mobile device. VKLiQ will market to all potential users as well by offering internship programs to selected students as they create and post events and market through other social media platforms. There has been a 60% drop of users age 18-24 from Facebook. That is more than 11 million young people since 2011. Yet their industry shows an almost 100% growth in the last 3 years. They currently have no competitors in this market space.

Dr. Kazmer’s practice model is to allow the body to heal naturally with conservative therapy and using surgical intervention only as the last treatment option. This philosophy is based on his extensive experience with all types of patients young and old. This method is conservative, yet innovative and effective for all foot & ankle disorders.

Description: OutlookCloud provides a solution for enterprise users to outsource email attachments to the Cloud.
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, Silicon Valley, West Coast
Full Description: OutlookCloud provides a solution for enterprise users to outsource email attachments to the Cloud. Its Attachment Manager product is a Microsoft Outlook add-in program that transparently detaches/re-attaches attachments and embedded images to/from the Cloud, for example by using the Amazon S3 service. Attachment Manager offloads email storage at an attractive price of $0.10/GB/month or less by using the optional compression feature. Using the optional encryption feature and auto-generated random new password on each attachment, it guarantees that the email data is secure even though the data is stored in the Cloud. Attachment Manager currently support two storage providers 1) Amazon S3 or 2) A network drive (or local hard drive). More storage providers will be added in the future. Detaching could be fully automated and re-attaching is a simple mouse click. Furthermore, it is all transparent that it appears to the end user that the attachments are still in the message. At a nickel a month (assuming Amazon S3, 1GB attachments and 50% compression ratio), enterprise users can reduce their email storage so that it is faster and more efficient to search, index and browse. Not to mention, they can now finally stay comfortable under the measly email quota given by their CIO.

Description: COMMENTARY is America’s premier monthly magazine of opinion and a pivotal voice in American intellectual life.
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: COMMENTARY is America’s premier monthly magazine of opinion and a pivotal voice in American intellectual life. Since its inception in 1945, and increasingly after it emerged as the flagship of neoconservatism in the 1970s, the magazine has been consistently engaged with several large, interrelated questions: the fate of democracy and of democratic ideas in a world threatened by totalitarian ideologies; the state of American and Western security; the future of the Jews, Judaism, and Jewish culture in Israel, the United States, and around the world; and the preservation of high culture in an age of political correctness and the collapse of critical standards. Many of COMMENTARY’s articles have been controversial, and more than a few have been hugely influential, touchstones for debate and discussion in universities, among policy analysts in and out of government, within the ranks of professionals and community activists of all kinds, and in circles of serious thought worldwide. A large number of articles can be counted as landmarks of American letters and intellectual life. Agree with it or disagree with it, COMMENTARY cannot be ignored. To read it is to take part in the great American discussion.
Industry Groups: Content and Publishing, Media and Entertainment
